To use TensorFlow and Hugging Face Transformers libraries in your WordPress website page, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the libraries on your server: You can install TensorFlow and Hugging Face Transformers libraries on your server using pip. Log in to your server via SSH and run the following commands:
```
pip install tensorflow
pip install transformers
```
Make sure that you have the necessary permissions to install packages on the server.

1. Load the libraries in your WordPress page: You can load the libraries in your WordPress page using the wp\_enqueue\_script() function. In the header.php file of your WordPress theme, add the following code:
```php
<?php
function load_custom_scripts() {
    wp_enqueue_script('tensorflow', 'https://unpkg.com/@tensorflow/tfjs@3.12.0/dist/tf.min.js', array(), '3.12.0', false);
    wp_enqueue_script('transformers', 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@huggingface/tokenizers@0.10.3/dist/tokenizers.min.js', array(), '0.10.3', false);
}
add_action('wp_enqueue_scripts', 'load_custom_scripts');
?>
```
This code will load the TensorFlow and Hugging Face Transformers libraries in your WordPress page.

1. Use the libraries in your JavaScript code: Once the libraries are loaded, you can use them in your JavaScript code. For example, you can use the following code to load the T5 model from Hugging Face Transformers and paraphrase the input text:
```javascript
const model = await transformers.T5ForConditionalGeneration.fromPretrained('t5-base');
const tokenizer = await transformers.AutoTokenizer.fromPretrained('t5-base');
const inputText = 'This is the input text to be paraphrased.';
const inputs = tokenizer.encode(inputText);
const inputIds = tf.tensor([inputs.input_ids]);
const outputs = await model.generate(inputIds, { max_length: 50 });
const paraphrasedText = tokenizer.decode(outputs[0].toArray());
console.log(paraphrasedText);
```
Note that the above code is just an example and you may need to modify it to fit your specific use case. Also, make sure to test your code thoroughly before deploying it to production.

Creating a website with a database and various views can be a bit complicated. Here are the basic steps you can follow to create a simple website with a database and multiple views:

1. Choose a programming language: You can use any server-side programming language, but some popular options are PHP, Python, and Ruby. In this example, we will use PHP.
2. Set up a web server: You need a web server like Apache or Nginx to run your PHP code.
3. Create a database: You can use MySQL or PostgreSQL to create your database. You can create a database using phpMyAdmin, a web-based interface for managing MySQL databases.
4. Design your database schema: Before creating a database, you need to design the schema. In this example, we will create a table called "links" with columns for title, URL, description, tags, and category.
5. Create a form to input data: You can create a form using HTML and CSS to input data into your database.
6. Use PHP to handle form submissions: When the form is submitted, you need to use PHP to insert the data into the database.
7. Create multiple views: You can create multiple views using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. In this example, we will create gallery, table, and list views.
8. Use JavaScript to switch between views: You can use JavaScript to switch between views. In this example, we will use jQuery to switch between views.
9. Use CSS to style your website: You can use CSS to style your website. You can use color-coded tags to organize and categorize your links.

Here's a sample code to help you get started:

HTML:
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Links</title>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
	<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
	<script src="script.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
	<div class="header">
		<h1>My Links</h1>
	</div>
	<div class="content">
		<div class="view-selector">
			<button class="view-btn" data-view="gallery">Gallery</button>
			<button class="view-btn" data-view="table">Table</button>
			<button class="view-btn" data-view="list">List</button>
		</div>
		<div class="view-container">
			<!-- Gallery view -->
			<div class="view" id="gallery-view">
				<!-- Display links in gallery view -->
			</div>
			<!-- Table view -->
			<div class="view" id="table-view">
				<!-- Display links in table view -->
			</div>
			<!-- List view -->
			<div class="view" id="list-view">
				<!-- Display links in list view -->
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</body>
</html>
```
